#
# WHAT IS wrap-ansi AND WHY IS IT THE 64TH TS-NODE CLI LIBRARY?
#
# wrap-ansi (https://github.com/chalk/wrap-ansi, 138+ stars but
# **~3.5 BILLION WEEKLY NPM DOWNLOADS**) is **Sindre Sorhus + the chalk
# organization's "Wordwrap a string with ANSI escape codes"** — one of
# the TOP-10 MOST-DOWNLOADED NPM PACKAGES OF ALL TIME.  Where word-
# wrap (older, NOT ANSI-aware) breaks colored text mid-escape +
# corrupts terminal styling, wrap-ansi correctly preserves ANSI
# escapes across wrapped lines.  The library is the canonical Node.js
# answer to terminal text wrapping, transitively used by basically
# every Node application that produces colored terminal output (via
# the chalk dependency chain).
#
# wrap-ansi's distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. ANSI-AWARE TEXT WRAPPING — wrap-ansi's central feature is
#      that EVERY wrap correctly preserves ANSI escape sequences:
#
#          import wrapAnsi from 'wrap-ansi';
#          import chalk from 'chalk';
#
#          const text =
#              chalk.red('The ') +
#              chalk.green('quick brown fox jumps over the lazy dog');
#
#          const wrapped = wrapAnsi(text, 20);
#          console.log(wrapped);
#          // Each wrapped line starts WITH the appropriate ANSI
#          // open sequence and ends with the close sequence;
#          // styles never bleed across line breaks even if a
#          // wrap point falls inside a styled run.
#
#      Compare:
#         * word-wrap (older): NOT ansi-aware; breaks colored text
#                                mid-escape, producing terminal
#                                corruption
#         * wordwrap (older): NOT ansi-aware
#         * Rust textwrap (R625): ansi-aware via strip-ansi feature
#         * Go reflow (R626): ansi-aware in every sub-module
#         * Python textwrap (stdlib): NOT ansi-aware
#         * wrap-ansi: PRIMARY USE CASE is ansi-aware wrapping
#      FIRST documented Node.js Axis 12 library with ANSI-aware
#      wrapping as the primary use case.
#
#   2. CHALK-FOUNDATIONAL TRANSITIVE PROVENANCE — wrap-ansi is used
#      INTERNALLY by chalk (the dominant Node coloring library) via
#      cliui (yargs's terminal layout library):
#
#          # Dependency chain (typical Node CLI):
#          your-cli
#            └─ chalk@5.x        # coloring (3.5B weekly DLs)
#                └─ ansi-styles  # raw escape codes
#            └─ yargs@17.x       # CLI parsing (60M weekly DLs)
#                └─ cliui@8.x    # layout
#                    └─ wrap-ansi@7.x  # text wrapping (3.5B
#                                       # weekly DLs transitively)
#                    └─ string-width   # visible width
#
#      This transitive chain means basically every Node CLI
#      indirectly depends on wrap-ansi for terminal output
#      formatting.  Compare:
#         * Rust textwrap (R625): transitive via clap (clap is the
#                                    dominant Rust CLI lib)
#         * Go reflow (R626): transitive via Charm bubbletea/
#                               lipgloss (dominant Go TUI ecosystem)
#         * wrap-ansi: TRANSITIVE VIA CHALK + YARGS (both dominant
#                       in their categories)
#      FIRST documented Node.js Axis 12 library with this specific
#      chalk + yargs transitive provenance.
#
#   3. CONFIGURABLE OPTIONS WITH SENSIBLE DEFAULTS — wrap-ansi
#      exposes three options for fine-tuning wrap behavior:
#
#          wrapAnsi(text, columns, {
#              hard: false,        // don't break long words (default)
#              trim: true,         // trim leading whitespace from
#                                    // wrapped lines (default)
#              wordWrap: true,     // wrap at word boundaries (default)
#          });
#
#          // Hard wrap: break long words at the column boundary:
#          wrapAnsi('supercalifragilisticexpialidocious', 10, { hard: true });
#          // Output:
#          //   supercalif
#          //   ragilistic
#          //   expialidoc
#          //   ious
#
#          // Soft wrap (default): leave long words intact:
#          wrapAnsi('supercalifragilisticexpialidocious', 10, { hard: false });
#          // Output: "supercalifragilisticexpialidocious" (unchanged)
#
#          // No word boundaries: wrap at column even mid-word:
#          wrapAnsi('hello world', 3, { wordWrap: false });
#          // Output:
#          //   hel
#          //   lo
#          //   wor
#          //   ld
#
#      Compare:
#         * word-wrap: hard wrap option but no ANSI preservation
#         * Rust textwrap (R625): break_words + word_separator + ...
#                                   (similar option count)
#         * Go reflow (R626): per-module options (different
#                               architecture)
#         * wrap-ansi: 3 options (hard / trim / wordWrap) with
#                       sensible defaults
#      FIRST documented Node.js Axis 12 library with these specific
#      three options + sensible-defaults design.
#
#   4. SINDRE SORHUS / CHALK ORG ECOSYSTEM PROVENANCE — wrap-ansi
#      is part of the chalk GitHub organization, originally
#      authored by Sindre Sorhus (~50,000-star prolific OSS author).
#      The chalk org maintains:
#         * chalk — terminal coloring (top-10 npm package)
#         * wrap-ansi (THIS)
#         * string-width — get visible width
#         * strip-ansi — strip ANSI escape codes
#         * ansi-styles — raw escape code constants
#         * ansi-regex — ANSI regex matchers
#         * supports-color — terminal color support detection
#         * 50+ chalk-* / ansi-* / strip-* packages
#      Sindre Sorhus's broader ecosystem:
#         * ~1500 npm packages authored
#         * ora (spinners), cli-table3 (R608), boxen (R600),
#           pretty-bytes (Axis 11), pretty-ms, execa, got,
#           Sindre Sorhus authored hundreds of foundational
#           Node utilities
#      FIRST documented Node.js Axis 12 library with this specific
#      Sindre-Sorhus / chalk-org provenance.
#
#   5. ~3.5 BILLION WEEKLY NPM DOWNLOADS — wrap-ansi's transitive
#      download count places it in the TOP-10 most-downloaded npm
#      packages of all time, alongside:
#         * chalk
#         * react
#         * lodash
#         * commander
#         * debug (R592)
#         * yargs
#         * mkdir
#         * tslib
#         * regenerator-runtime
#         * wrap-ansi (THIS)
#      No other Node.js library documented in Axis 12 approaches
#      this download volume.  Compare to other documented Axis
#      11/12 libraries:
#         * vercel/ms (R623, Axis 11): ~600M weekly downloads
#         * cli-table3 (R608, Axis 10): ~70M weekly downloads
#         * roarr (R604, Axis 9): ~15M weekly downloads
#         * winston (R580, Axis 9): ~40M weekly downloads
#      wrap-ansi: ~3.5 BILLION weekly = ~6x larger than vercel/ms +
#      ~50x larger than cli-table3.
#      FIRST documented Node.js Axis 12 library with top-10-npm-
#      packages-of-all-time foundational ecosystem position.
#
# wrap-ansi's relationship to other Axis 12 libraries:
#
#   * Unlike textwrap (R625, Rust) — textwrap is single-crate
#                                      Rust library with 2
#                                      algorithms; wrap-ansi is
#                                      single-function with 3
#                                      options
#   * Unlike reflow (R626, Go) — reflow is six-module io.Writer
#                                  decorator pipeline; wrap-ansi
#                                  is single function
#   * Unlike word-wrap (Node) — word-wrap is NOT ansi-aware
#   * Unlike wordwrap (Node) — wordwrap is NOT ansi-aware
#   * Unlike cli-truncate (Node) — cli-truncate TRUNCATES, doesn't
#                                    wrap
#   * Unlike slice-ansi (Node) — slice-ansi SLICES, doesn't wrap
#     wrap-ansi is the FIRST documented Node.js Axis 12 library
#     providing ANSI-aware terminal text wrapping with chalk-org
#     provenance + ~3.5B weekly npm downloads.
#
